04991nam a22008775i 9783110691771DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020943507  a97831106917717 a10.1515/97831106917712doi  a(DE-B1597)544684  a(OCoLC)1202477513  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0190002bisacsh1 aBoysen, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNothingness, Negativity, and Nominalism in Shakespeare and Petrarch /cBenjamin Boysen. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (X, 185 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tI. Introduction -- tII. Petrarch and the Triumph of Exile -- tIII. Rerum vulgarium fragmenta: Petrarch’s Labyrinthine Mirror -- tIV. Shakespeare’s “Nihilism” -- tV. Early Modernity and the Foil of Contrarieties -- tVI. Literature -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeing exposed to the Nominalist expansion in early modernity, Petrarch and Shakespeare are highly preoccupied with a Nominalist dimension of language and representation. Against this background, the study shows how these Renaissance poets advanced a special notion of subjectivity and identity as rooted in negativity, otherness, and representation. The book thus argues for a new understanding of negative modes of subjectivity in Petrarch and Shakespeare. A new and sharpened understanding emerging from an interpretation of Francesco Petrarch’s notion of exile and of love in his great poetical cycle Rerum vulgarium fragmenta as well as a meticulous examination of the concept of nothingness in William Shakespeare’s works. Petrarch and Shakespeare poetically show how identity is alien and decentred – yet also free and expanding. In other words, these poets illustrate how subjectivity is constituted by heterogeneity. Moreover, pointing to other examples of this negative subjectivity in Renaissance philosophy and poetry, the study suggests that these models for subjectivity could be extended to other early modern writers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aNegativität. 4aNominalismus. 4aSubjektivität. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aEarly Modernity.  anominalism.  anothingness.  asubjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package 2021z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831106918560 cprintz978311069167240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311069177140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110691771423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110691771.jpg  a978-3-11-065906-1  De Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCb2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-075070-6  DG Ebook Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075072-0  DG Ebook Package English 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  a